<Project
  title="Cooperative Capabilities of AI Systems"
  description="Undergraduate dissertation on multi-agent reinforcement learning: how communication constraints and reward design shape emergent cooperation between autonomous agents."
  eyebrow="Undergraduate dissertation"
  year="2025 — 2026"
  role="Research, experimentation & analysis"
  stack={['PyTorch', 'PettingZoo', 'PPO', 'MARL', 'Reinforcement Learning']}
  next={{ title: 'Neuroplastic Collective Intelligence', href: '/projects/neuroplastic-collective-intelligence' }}
>
  <p class="lede">
    When autonomous agents learn side by side, cooperation is not something you program — it is
    something that emerges, or fails to. My dissertation asked what makes the difference: how do
    communication constraints and reward design shape the cooperative behaviours that arise
    between learning agents?
  </p>

  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>
    Much of contemporary AI progress is empirical, but performance is often constrained less by
    data than by architecture and optimisation. Multi-agent reinforcement learning makes this
    vivid: the same learning algorithm can produce coordination or chaos depending on what agents
    are rewarded for and how much they are allowed to say to one another. I set out to study that
    sensitivity systematically — treating cooperation itself as the object of measurement.
  </p>

  <h2>Approach</h2>
  <p>
    I implemented PPO-based agents in PyTorch and trained them in PettingZoo simulation
    environments, then ran controlled experiments across two axes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Communication bandwidth</strong> — restricting how much information agents could
      exchange, from silence up to rich channels, and observing which communication strategies
      emerged under each constraint.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reward design</strong> — varying how credit was distributed between individual and
      shared outcomes, from fully selfish to fully collective incentive structures.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The focus throughout was experimentation and evaluation: defining measurable signatures of
    coordination, then analysing the strategies agents actually converged on rather than the ones
    the incentive design intended.
  </p>

  <h2>The counterintuitive result</h2>
  <div class="pull">
    Selfish incentives produced the most cooperation. Agents rewarded individually coordinated
    better than agents rewarded collectively — a result I traced back to the credit assignment
    problem.
  </div>
  <p>
    Under shared rewards, no agent could tell which of its actions had actually helped, and
    learning signals dissolved into noise; under individual rewards, the gradient each agent
    received was clean enough to learn behaviours that happened to be mutually beneficial.
    Cooperation, in other words, was bottlenecked by optimisation — not by intent. That finding
    reshaped how I think about collective systems, and it is what pushed me deeper into the
    mathematics of reinforcement learning.
  </p>

  <h2>Where it’s going</h2>
  <p>
    The work earned First Class marks and is now being prepared for workshop submission. It also
    seeded my current research: if credit assignment limits what fixed communication structures
    can achieve, the natural next question is whether the structure itself should learn — which
    is exactly what my work on neuroplastic collective intelligence explores.
  </p>
</Project>
